# Savvy — Private Secretary

Message from the dev:
As a PhD student who was juggling classes, research, personal health issues, a social life, and more, I struggled for months to keep a strict calendar (as a type B person). I was constantly changing my own plans due to things like work taking longer than expected or friends asking me to get lunch.
I had the idea for this secretary 6 months before I created it, because I wasn't sure if it would even be necessary. Now that I use it consistently, it has made it so much easier for me to organize my life. Remember something you need to do during class? Text Savvy "Hey, remind me to do this some time tomorrow."
Need to completely restructure your day around a new event? Just ask it to. Want to prioritize your new years resolutions and long-term goals? It'll try to fit 15 minutes a day for you to practice your skill or work on your personal projects. I won't say its perfect, and oftentimes I still need to provide it
some structure on the calendar or email styles first - but the longer you use it, the better it gets. I named it Savvy after my childhood nickname, because I thought of it like a mini-me. I hope Savvy helps you as much as it has helped me. 

A self-hosted AI secretary that connects Claude to your Google Calendar, Gmail, Tasks, and a local diary, with two-way Signal messaging and persistent memory. All long-term storage and retrieval stays on your machine. Only the current message and a small context window are sent to the API.


## Features

- **Two interfaces:** Runs as a desktop REPL and as a Signal bot you can text from your phone. Both share the same memory and toolset.
- **35+ local tools.** Create, update, move, and delete calendar events across multiple Google accounts. Search Gmail, draft replies, send messages, manage labels, archive threads. Manage Google Tasks and task lists. Store and retrieve diary entries and local notes.
- **Persistent local memory.** SQLite stores all conversations, extracted facts, and session metadata. Ollama generates embeddings locally with `nomic-embed-text` so the semantic memory index never leaves your machine. The retrieval layer combines recency and relevance to inject the most useful past context into each turn.
- **Automatic fact extraction.** After each exchange, a second model call pulls out concrete commitments, deadlines, and preferences and stores them separately from the conversation log.
- **Multi-account Google support.** Personal and work accounts can be linked simultaneously. Calendar defaults to one account by config, while email reads from both.
- **Proactive notification scheduler.** Optional systemd-managed background process that can send context-aware Signal messages (with quiet-hours and daily-budget enforcement) without the main app running.

I intend to add more tools going forward for my personal use, including linking the Google Home API to replace the default Gemini with Savvy. The pipe dream is to be able to run local music from my machine, 
control my TV and access my local movies, and avoid ads entirely. If you would like a new tool, feel free to let me know!

